<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870710-0046 </DOCNO><HL> Failed Banks in Texas,Colorado Are Closed,Set to Reopen Today</HL><DD> 07/10/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Banks in Texas and Colorado were closed, bringing the number of bank failures this year to 100, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.    The failed institutions were Red Oak State Bank, Red Oak, Texas, which had assets of $40.5 million, and First Continental Bank of Rockrimmon, Colorado Springs, Colo., which had assets of $7.6 million.    The sole office of Red Oak State, closed yesterday by state regulators, was scheduled to reopen with the same name today as a newly chartered subsidiary of ROSB Bancorp Inc., also of Red Oak. The failed bank held $37.7 million in 8,300 deposit accounts and was the 34th Texas bank to close this year.    First Continental's office, closed yesterday by the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency, was scheduled to reopen today as a branch of Valley Bank, Security, Colo. First Continental, which held deposits of $5.7 million in 1,000 accounts, was the eighth bank to fail in Colorado this year. </TEXT></DOC>